      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         <p>Henry Botkin (1896-1983) was an American abstract, modern and expressionist painter and
            illustrator; he was known for his figure-views, still lifes, and non-objective
            paintings. He was active in artistic circles, served as president of four major art
            organizations (Artists Equity Association, American Abstract Artists, Group 256
            Provincetown, and Federation of Modern Painters and Sculptors), and in 1955 organized
            the first exhibition of American abstract art at the Museum of Modern Art in Tokyo,
            Japan.</p>
      </bioghist>
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Henry Botkin Papers</emph> consists of biographical material, correspondence, manuscript material, photographs, published material and subject files.</p><p><emph render="bold">Biographical material</emph> contains a biographical sketch of Botkin from the 1948 Marquis <emph render="italic">International Who's Who</emph>.</p><p><emph render="bold">Correspondence</emph> includes letters to or from Botkin's wife and fellow painter Anna Walinska, along with a few unidentified letters.</p><p><emph render="bold">Manuscripts</emph> contains an assortment of material by and about Botkin, including a book outline, press releases, some pencil sketches, speeches and discussions.</p><p><emph render="bold">Photographs</emph> are of Botkin, his work, and the work of others.</p><p>The bulk of <emph render="bold">Published material</emph> is comprised of newspaper clippings by and about Botkin; there are also some reproductions of Botkin's work and some exhibit material.  Two books originally with the collection have been transferred to Rare Books for cataloging.</p><p><emph render="bold">Subject files</emph> includes financial material (bills, receipts, etc.), an essay  on abstrac art in Japan by Sabro Hasagawa, a few building plans and meeting minutes from several organizations to which Botkin belonged.</p>
      </scopecontent>
